Hello Karel

Have you ever felt something's wrong, but you can't pinpoint what it is?

Even though you know there are many tiny details?

I know that feeling well. Over the past 13 years, I've trained my eye to spot these details.

This skill comes with practice.

Nobody can spot everything right away, and there might be many solutions for each problem. The key is to notice, suspect something is wrong, and figure out what exactly.

By the way, if you're interested in honing your UI/UX skills, I'm currently working on a course where I redesign an existing app.

I'll soon be opening pre-sales for the first 100 people at a special price. Get notified when I open the presale to secure your spot.

One of the goals is to train your eye to find problems and be able to explain why they're problems (e.g., by referring to design principles, UX laws, competitor analysis, or at least common sense).

Let's go over the first page of the app and spot what problems it has.

â€‹

Initial screen

After logging in, we'll see the following page, which is a dashboard. Apparently, there are many issues, but the goal is not to get stuck with immediate solutions.

The goal is to spot as many issues as you can right away. Then, after analyzing a few pages, the solutions might be easier to come up with. But if you can't see the exact problems, then you won't be able to fix them.

Let me share what I noticed right away. It's very superficial and basic, yet this is how my mind works - going from obvious things that are on the surface, and then going deep (which is harder and requires more time).

Also, remember, there are design principles that exist for a reason. Knowing them will help you justify your thoughts and decisions.

â€‹

Sidebar

The first thing that grabbed my attention is having an icon next to "My Account." The other items don't have any icons, so we are not consistent here.

Not to mention that there is my avatar in the top-right corner of the app, which presumably has to do something with my account as well.

The second thing that confused me is the plus icon. It expands the menu, but a more commonly used icon for that purpose is an arrow pointing down, also called a chevron.

The third issue is that the icons have a primary color, which feels like something important that we can "add," instead of a helper icon that expands the menu.

The primary color is called primary for a reason and should be used for primary actions.

â€‹

Cards

Here you can spot a few things related to visuals:

  1. The border radius of the cards is different, breaking the consistency.
  2. The cards, avatars, dropdowns - everything has a shadow, and it stands out too much. We can even remove it, since the cards are placed on a gray background, so they will not be lost anyway.
  3. One card has a title, another one doesn't.

But there are many more issues.

  1. Alignment. One of the C.R.A.P. principles. Everything is center-aligned, which is known to be a bad practice in most cases.
  2. Hierarchy. There are too many colors, sizes, and variations in boldness, creating a chaotic look.
  3. Spacing. This is a violation of the proximity/locality rule.
  4. Copy. Buttons should have actions in them. Engagement, Dashboard, Tweepsmap - these are not actions. Tweepsmap is a mystery. The last one, "view," is okay but can be improved further (view what?).
